Here is an example of an Airplane class in Python:

```python
class Airplane:
    def __init__(self, make, model, year, max_speed, odometer, is_flying=False):
        """Initialize the airplane attributes."""
        self.make = make
        self.model = model
        self.year = year
        self.max_speed = max_speed
        self.odometer = odometer
        self.is_flying = is_flying

    def take_off(self):
        """Simulate the airplane taking off."""
        if self.is_flying:
            print(f"This {self.year} {self.make} {self.model} is already flying.")
        else:
            self.is_flying = True
            print(f"The {self.year} {self.make} {self.model} takes off.")

    def fly(self, distance):
        """Simulate the airplane flying."""
        if not self.is_flying:
            print(f"You need to take off first, before flying the {self.year} {self.make} {self.model}.")
        else:
            self.odometer += distance
            print(f"The {self.year} {self.make} {self.model} flew for {distance} miles.")

    def land(self):
        """Simulate the airplane landing."""
        if not self.is_flying:
            print(f"The {self.year} {self.make} {self.model} has already landed.")
        else:
            self.is_flying = False
            print(f"The {self.year} {self.make} {self.model} has landed.")

    def read_odometer(self):
        """Read the airplane's odometer."""
        print(f"This {self.year} {self.make} {self.model} has flown for {self.odometer} miles.")
```

The `Airplane` class has attributes to represent the important properties of the airplane, such as its make, model, year, maximum speed, and odometer reading. The `is_flying` attribute tracks whether the airplane is currently flying or not. The class also has methods to simulate taking off, flying, and landing, as well as reading the odometer.

